 guillotined on April 5, 1794, at the height of The Terror, on the same day as Georges Jacques Danton.From Dobruska's ideas, which were widely used between the late eighteenth century and the first decades of the nineteenth century without attribution to their author, emerge some of the key concepts of the social sciences as we know them today. An enthusiastic and unfortunate revolutionary and sometimes a brilliant theorist, Moses Dobruska deserves a role of his own in the history of sociology. Click here for a video book presentation by the author.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Freie Universität Berlin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aFrühe Neuzeit. 4aJudentum. 4aSozialphilosophie. 4aSoziologische Theorie. 4aVerfassungstheorie. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aConstitutional Theories.  aEarly Modern Jewry.  aFrench Revolution.  aHistory of sociological thought.  aIntellectual History.  aSocial Philosophy.2 aFreie Universität Berlinefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022 Englishz978311099296008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2022z9783110992939oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831107588630 cprintz978311067353140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110758825zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110758825zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97831107